                <body>
                    

<opener><address><addrLine>St. Mary's Dominican College,</addrLine>
<addrLine>Muckross Park,</addrLine>
<addrLine>Donnybrook,</addrLine>
<addrLine>Dublin, S.</addrLine></address> <dateline><date>25th May 1916</date></dateline></opener> <note>P.S. When you  <lb/>feel equal, we  <lb/>should like to <lb/>have a visit  <lb/>from you.</note>  <salute>Dear M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. O'Rahilly,</salute> <p>You must think  <lb/>it very strange that I  <lb/>never wrote a line to <lb/> offer you our deepest <lb/> sympathy in the biggest <lb/> sorrow of your life.</p> <p>Believe me it was
        
    

    
         
        <pb n="2731" facs="#L1916_1052_img_2731"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>through no want of  <lb/>sympathy, but there are <lb/> times when a stranger's <lb/> letter might jar and <lb/> in a grief such as  <lb/>yours I thought it  <lb/>better to wait a little  <lb/>before intruding. <lb/>May God comfort  <lb/>your poor broken heart,  <lb/>as He alone can. You  <lb/>have the comfort of  <lb/>knowing that your dear <lb/>husband was a good, <lb/> holy man and died  <lb/>a holy, happy death. <lb/>We have prayed much  <lb/>for him and you.</p> <p>I hope the boys <lb/> will be a great comfort
        
    
         
        <pb n="2732" facs="#L1916_1052_img_2732"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>to you now.</p> <p>If you get any mortuary <lb/> cards of your dear husband <lb/> may I ask for a few. <lb/>We should like to remember <lb/> such a noble soul R.I.P. <lb/>Joined by the Sisters in <lb/> deepest sympathy, love  <lb/>to my old Children.</p> <closer><salute>Yours very sincerely in J.C.</salute> <signed><hi rend="underline">S.M. Martina</hi></signed></closer> <lb/>O.S.D.
        
    
                </body>
            </text>

        
            
        
            
        
            
        

         

